result.execSummary:
The defendant Jenoria R Currie was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Jenoria R Currie is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Jenoria R Currie was found guilty of Disorderly Conduct. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:01 PM Defendant Jenoria R Currie in court.  Attorney Jeffrey W. Jensen Jr. in court for Jenoria R Currie.  Prosecuting attorney Alyssa M. Schaller in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
Case called early. There are no victims on this case. 

Prosecuting attorney moves to amend to Disorderly Conduct contrary to section 13.102(c)(8)  of the Waukesha County Code of Ordinances, and moves to dismiss count #1.  Court approves amendment.  No contest plea entered.  Court finds the defendant guilty.

Court orders the following:
COSTS: $181.50 to be paid within 30 days or civil judgment entered subject to collections, as penalty for non payment of fine.
Plea/sentencing hearing on August 23, 2022 at 03:30 pm.

After reviewing PT offer with the State, Atty Jensen requests a plea/sentencing hearing.  Plea/sentencing hearing scheduled for August 23, 2022 at 03:30 pm.
